  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_835074991" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/835074991" />
    <a title="Dorothea" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6638679-dorothea"><img alt="Dorothea" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1335630852p2/6638679.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/835074991?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dorothea" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dorothea" href="/user/show/6638679-dorothea">Dorothea</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer835074991" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12991280389439262110">I didn&apos;t expect the matter of this book -- a bard captured by Fairyland -- to be my cup of tea. I read enough about Fairyland in high school to last the rest of my life, and I tend to think of bardic protagonists as the fantasy genre&apos;s version of writer protagonists in literary fiction -- the exception to my rule of enjoying whenever someone writes a story about their own job.<br/><br/>However, perhaps because Ellen Kushner is a sort of bard herself, as well as a writer, I did like reading about the prota</span>
  <span id="freeText12991280389439262110" style="display:none">I didn't expect the matter of this book -- a bard captured by Fairyland -- to be my cup of tea. I read enough about Fairyland in high school to last the rest of my life, and I tend to think of bardic protagonists as the fantasy genre's version of writer protagonists in literary fiction -- the exception to my rule of enjoying whenever someone writes a story about their own job.<br /><br />However, perhaps because Ellen Kushner is a sort of bard herself, as well as a writer, I did like reading about the protagonist. And while I didn't like the protagonist very much when I first met him, I don't think I was supposed to; because this is a story about how he changes. How suitable that a beautiful man who can cause trouble and get himself out of it by his own eloquence (but who leaves others -- particularly, women who are susceptible to his beauty -- in trouble) should find himself in a situation where he's nearly powerless, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[at the instigation of another woman who's susceptible to his beauty, but who is so powerful that she can't be troubled by him, and can take away much of his eloquence. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Part of what interests me is that what happens to Thomas is a way of thinking about rape. The story doesn't make it unquestionably clear that any rapes occur, but it is certainly about sex and power. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Thomas, before he goes to Fairyland, has and uses sexual power. We know that his person, music, and speech are attractive to many women; and that he's had many sexual partners; and that one of them is a lady of the court who's not supposed to have sex until she marries a man of higher class than Thomas; and that (this is a thing that happens on-screen, unlike the previous items) Thomas is very capable of verbally romancing young a woman as though he were in love with only her, when he's not sure how he feels. Though we don't see this happen, it seems likely that Thomas has pursued sexual relationships with women who, had they not been overwhelmed by his beauty and golden tongue and close attentions, would have decided that the potential negative consequences of sleeping with him outweighed the temptation.<br /><br />So then, what happens to Thomas when he wanders in the wood and meets the Queen of Faerie? In her presence, he becomes nearly incapable of thought. All he really knows is that he wants her. Then she warns him. She says (I paraphrase), "You can kiss me, and if you kiss me we will have sex, and if we have sex I will own your body and take you away from Earth to Fairyland where you will be my captive for seven years, and yes, all those stories you've sung about what Fairyland is like are true." Fair warning! That's what she thinks. Thomas accuses her of having enchanted him already, and she denies it, but -- of course she has. She wants him, and she <i>is</i> magic, and therefore he wants everything she wants. Then, Thomas blames himself because he always <i>did</i> want Fairyland to be true and to go there and have adventures, so when he kissed her he chose what he wanted, even though Fairyland turned out to be horrible at times.<br /><br />But did he really choose freely, in that compelling presence? I don't think it's a coincidence that when I try to puzzle this out, I think about it in the same way that I'd think about the lady-in-waiting who loved Thomas's music, whom he loved and left. We don't meet her in the story so I don't know how she felt when she chose Thomas. I'm quite sure she did want him, and that he did not make her feel as though she had no choice. But did she really choose him freely, and the fear and loneliness and deception that came afterwards? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />Disempowering someone in a way they haven't experienced before -- a simple way to change them. So Thomas is changed after seven years. I'm not sure it was even necessary to <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[give him that two-edged gift, on his departure from Fairyland, of a voice that can speak only the truth. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> But then, as he hadn't lost any of his beauty or artistry, perhaps his vulnerability would have worn off soon enough otherwise.<br /><br />I think what I loved most, in the later part of the book, was Elspeth pointing out what she had done for seven years. She too had been powerless in new ways, had suffered and striven and changed. But we the audience spent those years with Thomas, not Elspeth, because -- as she says -- her servitude, as a poor woman, a laborer and wife and mother, is too common to be made into a story or a song. Elspeth and I both are happy to hear all of Thomas's stories and songs. She wouldn't, and I don't, resent hearing about Thomas in fairyland instead of Elspeth on the ridge. But her bitter commentary gave <i>Thomas the Rhymer</i> an honesty it would otherwise have lacked.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12991280389439262110" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


