<div id="review_2234083006" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2234083006" />
    <a title="Kes" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70325177-kes"><img alt="Kes" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2234083006?book_show_action=true">Dec 31, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kes" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kes" href="/user/show/70325177-kes">Kes</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780307418647" href="/book/show/7441949-thomas-the-rhymer">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70325177-kes?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/70325177-kes?shelf=read-2017">read-2017</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2234083006" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3585974381985967489">This is a light fantasy novel which retells the story of Thomas the Rhymer, who is taken under the hill to Elfland for seven years. On his return, he is unable to tell a lie. <br/><br/>I really enjoyed how lyrical the writing is. It&apos;s a story told in four parts:<br/><br/><a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[1) We start from Gavin&apos;s perspective. On a rainy night, he and his wife, Meg, gives a man shelter. This is Thomas, who, over the years, comes back to visit Gavin and Meg, bearing them gifts each time. He&apos;s eventually treated as a fos</span></span>
  <span id="freeText3585974381985967489" style="display:none">This is a light fantasy novel which retells the story of Thomas the Rhymer, who is taken under the hill to Elfland for seven years. On his return, he is unable to tell a lie. <br /><br />I really enjoyed how lyrical the writing is. It's a story told in four parts:<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[1) We start from Gavin's perspective. On a rainy night, he and his wife, Meg, gives a man shelter. This is Thomas, who, over the years, comes back to visit Gavin and Meg, bearing them gifts each time. He's eventually treated as a foster son for the childless couple. We also see his relationship with Elspeth, a girl from the neighbouring farm, develop. We end when Thomas disappears unexpectedly: leaving his harp behind on a trip to the woods. I liked how matter-of-fact his voice is.<br /><br />2) We switch to Thomas's perspective, as he is greeted by the Queen of Elfland. In return for a kiss, he gives her seven years of service and is taken under the hill to Elfland. Thomas solves a riddle about a knight and helps him obtain justice; on that same occasion, he is also deprived of his voice. He then spends the remainder of the seven years (it's clear that time passes oddly) with the Elf Queen, playing his harp and having sex. Eventually, he is released back onto Earth, where he stumbles back to Meg and Gavin. He's also given a gift of truth.<br /><br />3) This is Meg's perspective about Thomas's return. Thomas is apparently physically unchanged from his trip, save a sort of fey appearance about him. I like Meg's observations about people. It also helped me appreciate Meg and Gavin's relationship: about how they complement each other. Meg's appreciation of the undertones between Thomas's return help the reader understand the difficulty of Thomas returning to Gavin's affections (Gavin is initially suspicious of Thomas's claim that he ventured into Elfland) and Thomas being reunited with Elspeth (who has since married). We also see Thomas' initial difficulty with his truth telling abilities: when someone asks him a question, he answers truthfully, and it takes him time to turn aside the question. (This causes him difficulties, as he was known for his fair tongue. <br /><br />Eventually, Thomas goes off to regain his fortune as a bard. Over time (I appreciated this - no instant!love/forgiveness), he wins his way back to Elspeth's favour and they get married.<br /><br />The book could have ended here.<br /><br />4) The last part is Elspeth's perspective about Thomas. It felt a little extraneous, and it covers a few incidents: Thomas meeting the king and queen (comments are passed on how he speaks simply now, rather than his tongue being full of magic), and Thomas meeting his first son Hugh of Errol (by Lilias Drummond). The latter incident also comes with its angst: Thomas learns that his son will die within the year, and is unable to prevent it. Lastly, we see Elspeth watching Thomas die. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I felt Elspeth's perspective was unnecessary, but it was a fun read all the same. It's a slow book, but the writing makes it an easy read. I admired the song excerpts, and the author even goes into the composition process as Thomas writes a song - him substituting words, thinking of how to add beginnings to middle bits.<br /><br />2.5 stars - this isn't a <i>novel</i> book, but it's a fun read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3585974381985967489" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


