    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3056170908" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3056170908" />
    <a title="Steven" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5369906-steven"><img alt="Steven" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442515017p2/5369906.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3056170908?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steven" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steven" href="/user/show/5369906-steven">Steven</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3056170908" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3835143940671717532">I picked this up some time ago after reading a review from one of my Goodreads friends (Werner) and finally got back to it. This is a masterfully told retelling of a Scottish legend/myth of a harper who spends time in Elfland as the price of a kiss (interpreted as perhaps something more) from the Queen of Elfland. The characters are right for the period and are very human, both with their emotions and failures. There seem to be no real &quot;winners&quot; in this book, though the four characters who each </span>
  <span id="freeText3835143940671717532" style="display:none">I picked this up some time ago after reading a review from one of my Goodreads friends (Werner) and finally got back to it. This is a masterfully told retelling of a Scottish legend/myth of a harper who spends time in Elfland as the price of a kiss (interpreted as perhaps something more) from the Queen of Elfland. The characters are right for the period and are very human, both with their emotions and failures. There seem to be no real "winners" in this book, though the four characters who each tell a part of the first-person narrative are all protagonists. It's perhaps this approach that made me see this a four stars instead of five as I was not able to feel for one single character throughout the book.<br /><br />What I liked best about this book was that there were no heroic deeds to make one character seem superior to others. Thomas, his human friends and (later) human wife are all mortal and as capable of emotions and faults as any other person might and should be. While Thomas is chosen to go to Elfland and serve the queen there for 7 years, it is because he is a master of his art and not some miraculous creature beyond human. The Queen of Elfland is also created much as she should be. She is selfish, haughty, beyond human emotions, but also caring and capable of being seduced as she allows. The characters here truly stand out.<br /><br />If Scottish legends interest you, pick this book up. If good, readable and relatable characters interest you, pick this book up. It didn't get my 5 stars because I just can't imagine re-reading it, but it is very, very good and highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3835143940671717532" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


