<div id="review_3339783363" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3339783363" />
    <a title="Dannica Zulestin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28789176-dannica-zulestin"><img alt="Dannica Zulestin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428105952p2/28789176.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3339783363?book_show_action=true">May 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dannica Zulestin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dannica Zulestin" href="/user/show/28789176-dannica-zulestin">Dannica Zulestin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3339783363" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3315907324197471227">I read Swordspoint last year, and now this is my second Kushner. It&apos;s not quite as good as Swordspoint, but I think it&apos;s also just essentially very different--it&apos;s honestly more a fairy tale than a fantasy, if that makes sense. Very classically a fairy tale: the harper taken by the Fair Folk, a love with the fairy queen, etc etc. It still has Kushner&apos;s strength of worldbuilding. Both fairyland and plain old England, which Thomas starts in and returns to, have their own distinct flavor and their </span>
  <span id="freeText3315907324197471227" style="display:none">I read Swordspoint last year, and now this is my second Kushner. It's not quite as good as Swordspoint, but I think it's also just essentially very different--it's honestly more a fairy tale than a fantasy, if that makes sense. Very classically a fairy tale: the harper taken by the Fair Folk, a love with the fairy queen, etc etc. It still has Kushner's strength of worldbuilding. Both fairyland and plain old England, which Thomas starts in and returns to, have their own distinct flavor and their own distinct rules. There are also such interesting relationships, and two very different romances. A romance with a fairy queen, after all, is nothing like a romance with a farm girl. And which is the more important to Thomas or to the story is hard to say.<br /><br />So in that case, why only three stars? Well, I may up the rating to four later. But I think the book starts a bit slow, and the ending is not entirely satisfying. Also, there's the occasional weirdly sexist moment: Thomas's disgust just at seeing an old woman at one point, Thomas's remark on how the fairy queen can't bear children as if this is some fatal flaw, and similar moments along this vein... They feel true enough to Thomas's character (he's no angel), but they still are jarring moments in the narrative.<br /><br />A good read overall. I hope to read another Kushner novel soon--probably Privilege of the Sword.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3315907324197471227" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


